HashMap vs ConcurrentHashMap in Java

Both HashMap and ConcurrentHashMap store data as key → value pairs,
but they are used in different situations.

1. Thread Safety
HashMap
❌ Not thread-safe
Multiple threads can break data
ConcurrentHashMap
✅ Thread-safe
Designed for concurrent environments
2. Performance
Scenario	HashMap	ConcurrentHashMap
Single thread	Faster	Slightly slower
Multi-thread	Unsafe	Fast and safe

👉 ConcurrentHashMap is optimized for concurrency

3. Locking Mechanism
HashMap
No locking
Not safe for concurrent access
ConcurrentHashMap
Before Java 8:
used segment locking
Java 8+:
uses fine-grained locking + CAS (Compare-And-Swap)

👉 Instead of locking the whole map:

locks only part of the data
allows multiple threads to work simultaneously
4. Null Keys and Values
Feature	HashMap	ConcurrentHashMap
null key	✅ allowed	❌ not allowed
null value	✅ allowed	❌ not allowed

👉 Reason: avoids ambiguity in concurrent operations

5. Internal Behavior
HashMap
uses buckets
collisions → list / tree
not safe in multi-threading
ConcurrentHashMap
similar structure (buckets + tree)
but designed for safe concurrent access
reads are mostly non-blocking
6. Iteration Behavior
HashMap
may throw ConcurrentModificationException
ConcurrentHashMap
does NOT throw exception
uses weakly consistent iterator

👉 means:

can read data while it’s changing
may not reflect latest updates exactly
7. When to Use
Use HashMap when:
single-threaded application
no shared data
need maximum performance
Use ConcurrentHashMap when:
multi-threaded environment
shared data between threads
need safe and fast access
Summary
HashMap → fast, but not thread-safe
ConcurrentHashMap → thread-safe and scalable
main difference → concurrency handling
ConcurrentHashMap uses advanced locking (CAS + fine-grained locks)
Final Thought

👉 If multiple threads are involved → always prefer ConcurrentHashMap
👉 If not → HashMap is simpler and faster
